m provider v4+                                            \u2502\n\u2502  * code must pass terraform validate                                         \u2502\n\u2502  * code should be deployable without modification                            \u2502\n\u2502  * use best practices for production AKS                                     \u2502\n\u2502  * include tags on all resources                                             \u2502\n\u2502  * avoid deprecated Terraform arguments                                      \u2502\n\u2502  * use latest stable AKS version available from data source                  \u2502\n\u2502  * expose kubeconfig output securely                                         \u2502\n\u2502  * configure node resource group automatically                               \u2502\n\u2502  * include lifecycle and dependency handling where required                  \u2502\n\u2502  * generate complete modular Terraform structure                             \u2502\n\u2502  * ensure compatibility with Terraform 1.6+                                  \u2502\n\u2502                                                                              \u2502\n\u2502  IMPORTANT: DO NOT add NAT Gateways, Private Subnets, or Multi-AZ unless     \u2502\n\u2502  explicitly requested.                                                       \u2502\n\u2502  1. Identify necessary providers and resources.                              \u2502\n\u2502  2. You MUST provide a **Mermaid.js diagram string** representing the        \u2502\n\u2502  architecture.                                                               \u2502\n\u2502  3. The first line of your response must be: PROJECT_SLUG: <slug>            \u2502\n\u2502     - The slug MUST be a descriptive kebab-case name derived from the        \u2502\n\u2502  requirement (e.g., \"eks-public-cluster\", \"s3-versioned-bucket\").            \u2502\n\u2502     - NEVER use generic names like \"terraform-project\" or timestamps.        \u25